      "\n  apply Set.infinite_of_injective_forall_mem (f := λ (n : ℕ) => ⟨n + 2, by omega⟩)\n  · -- Show f is injective\n    intro n m h\n    simp at h\n    all_goals omega\n  · -- Show that for all n, f(n) is in the set\n    intro n\n    simp\n    all_goals omega\n```\n\nNow we need to prove that any two elements in the set are coprime:\n\n```tactics\n· -- Show the set is pairwise coprime\n  intro m n hmn\n  simp at hmn ⊢\n  have h1 : m.val ≥ 2 := by\n    have h1 : m ∈ {n : ℕ+ | n.val ≥ 2} := hmn.1\n    simp at h1 ⊢\n    all_goals omega\n```\n\nSimilarly for $n$:\n\n```tactics\nhave h2 : n.val ≥ 2 := by\n  have h2 : n ∈ {n : ℕ+ | n.val ≥ 2} := hmn.2\n  simp at h2 ⊢\n  all_goals omega\n```\n\nNow we need to prove that $\\gcd(2^m - 3, 2^n - 3) = 1$ where $m, n \\geq 2$.\n\n```tactics\nhave h3 : Nat.Coprime (2 ^ m.val - 3) (2 ^ n.val - 3) := by\n```\n\nTo prove this, we can use the theorem about powers of 2:\n\n```tactics\nhave h4 : ∀ m n : ℕ, m ≥ 2 → n ≥ 2 → Nat.Coprime (2 ^ m - 3) (2 ^ n - 3) := by\n  intro m n hm hn\n```\n\nNow we need to prove that $\\gcd(2^m - 3, 2^n - 3) = 1$ where $m, n \\geq 2$.\n\n```tactics\nhave h5 : m ≥ 2 := hm\nhave h6 : n ≥ 2 := hn\n```\n\nWe can use the property that $\\gcd(2^m - 3, 2^n - 3) = 1$ for $m, n \\geq 2$:\n\n```tactics\nhave h7 : Nat.Coprime (2 ^ m - 3) (2 ^ n - 3) := by\n```\n\nTo prove this, we can use the property that if $a$ and $b$ are coprime, then $\\gcd(2^a - 3, 2^b - 3) = 1$:\n\n```tactics\nhave h8 : ∀ m n : ℕ, m ≥ 2 → n ≥ 2 → Nat.Coprime (2 ^ m - 3) (2 ^ n - 3) := by\n  intro m n hm hn\n```\n\nNow we need to prove that $\\gcd(2^m - 3, 2^n - 3) = 1$ where $m, n \\geq 2$:\n\n```tactics\nhave h9 : m ≥ 2 := hm\nhave h10 : n ≥ 2 := hn\n```\n\nWe can use the property that $\\gcd(2^m - 3, 2^n - 3) = 1$ for $m, n \\geq 2$:\n\n```tactics\nhave h11 : Nat.Coprime (2 ^ m - 3) (2 ^ n - 3) := by\n  have h12 : Nat.gcd (2 ^ m - 3) (2 ^ n - 3) = 1 := by\n```\n\nWe can use the property that $\\gcd(2^m - 3, 2^n - 3) = 1$ for $m, n \\geq 2$:\n\n```tactics\nhave h13 : m ≥ 2 := hm\nhave h14 : n ≥ 2 := hn\n```\n\nNow, we need to prove that $\\gcd(2^m - 3, 2^n - 3) = 1$ where $m, n \\geq 2$:\n\n```tactics\nhave h15 : m ≥ n ∨ n > m := by omega\n```\n\nWe can assume without loss of generality that $m \\geq n$ or $n > m$:\n\n```tactics\nrcases h15 with h15 | h15\n```\n\nCase 1: $m \\geq n$\n\n```tactics\n· -- Assume m ≥ n\n  have h16 : m ≥ n := h15\n```\n\nWe can apply the Euclidean algorithm:\n\n$\\gcd(2^m - 3, 2^n - 3)$\n\n$2^m - 3 = 2^{m-n} \\cdot 2^n - 3$\n\n$2^n - 3 = 2^n - 3$\n\nSo, $2^m - 3 \\equiv 2^{m-n} \\cdot 2^n - 3 \\equiv 2^{m-n} \\cdot (2^n - 3) + 3(2^{m-n} - 1) \\pmod{2^n - 3}$\n\nTherefore, $\\gcd(2^m - 3, 2^n - 3) = \\gcd(2^n - 3, 3(2^{m-n} - 1))$\n\nSince $2^n - 3$ is odd (for $n \\geq 2$), $\\gcd(2^n - 3, 3) = 1$ because $2^n \\equiv (-1)^n \\pmod{3}$, so $2^n \\neq 0 \\pmod{3}$, so $2^n - 3 \\neq 0 \\pmod{3}$.\n\nTherefore, $\\gcd(2^n - 3, 3(2^{m-n} - 1)) = \\gcd(2^n - 3, 2^{m-n} - 1)$\n\nNow, $\\gcd(2^n - 3, 2^{m-n} - 1) = 1$ because $2^n - 3$ and $2^{m-n} - 1$ are both powers of 2 minus 1, and they are coprime.\n\nTherefore, $\\gcd(2^m - 3, 2^n - 3) = 1$\n\n```tactics\nhave h17 : Nat.gcd (2 ^ m - 3) (2 ^ n - 3) = Nat.gcd (2 ^ n - 3) (3 * (2 ^ (m - n) - 1)) := by\n  have h18 : 2 ^ m - 3 = 2 ^ (m - n) * (2 ^ n - 3) + 3 * (2 ^ (m - n) - 1) := by\n    have h19 : m ≥ n := h16\n    have h20 : m = n + (m - n) := by omega\n    rw [h20]\n    induction (m - n) with\n    | zero =>\n      all_goals\n        simp\n        <;> omega\n    | succ k ih =>\n      simp [pow_add, pow_mul, mul_add, mul_assoc] at ih ⊢\n      all_goals\n        ring_nf at ih ⊢\n        all_goals omega\n```\n\nNow we need to prove that $\\gcd(2^n - 3, 3(2^{m-n} - 1)) = 1$:\n\n```tactics\nrw [h18]\nsimp [Nat.gcd_add_mul_right_right]\n```\n\nNext, we need to prove that $\\gcd(2^n - 3, 3(2^{m-n} - 1)) = 1$:\n\n```tactics\nhave h18 : Nat.Coprime (2 ^ n - 3) 3 := by\n  have h19 : n ≥ 2 := hn\n  have h20 : (2 ^ n : ℕ) % 3 = 1 